body:
Wait imagine this:

Rose and Ten 2 get married the human way and they buy this huge house that looks bigger on the inside. They paint it blue in honor of ten. They then have a kid and that kid of course is part time lord and they have to explain to him/her all of the adventures they had together and the memories they shared but they never tell the kid that ten 2 isn’t the doctor in the memories and he gets sad when he talks of the memories that were transferred to him. They have another child and by this time the stories are just common knowledge in the family. Then one day they find a way to make another TARDIS in the other dimension, so they decide to do so taking the kids with them, sharing in the fun. Ten and Rose also are working their dream jobs, so by the time they retire they have saved enough to travel the world in the TARDIS 2. Not only do they feel alive and proud, they feel young at heart. They love their life as human beings and when all is said and done, they don’t regret anything.

body:
So I’m watching David and Billie’s panel from Emerald City Comicon and they’re talking about how much they enjoyed doing the Big Finish audiobooks, and Billie just casually says that she’s going to do some more…

THIS WAS NINE MONTHS AGO. SHE GAVE THE GAME AWAY NINE MONTHS AGO.

Bless David, he looked ever so confused when she said that, asking whether he was in them or whether she was going off on her own! NOW WE KNOW!

summary: “Well, he was devastated. I think Rose had helped him reform himself. I think Rose had influenced who he became when he...
body:
“Well, he was devastated. I think Rose had helped him reform himself. I think Rose had influenced who he became when he regenerated into me. I think her influence was very formative for the Doctor, having come out of this terrible war and all of these extraordinarily awful things that he’d been to and been borne witness to. And that she helped him recover, helped him become the man that he re-found. To lose her was devastating, and yet, as it went for the Doctor, kind of inevitable. That’s part of that tragedy of that character, that every relationship that he forms with anyone other than a Time Lord – and of course, there were none of them left – was, by its very nature, transient, because he’s effectively eternal next to a human being, who might get a hundred years if they’re lucky. So that’s one of the tragedies of that character that makes him sort of timeless. So yeah, to lose Rose – the woman who’d helped him rebuild who he was, and the woman he almost dared to fall in love with, I think – was devastating for him, and took him a long time to get over. And maybe he never did. He was certainly never quite over it while he was me.” - david tennant

david tennant admitting in the year 2018 that ten never recovered from losing rose (while referring to the tenth doctor in the first person)……. woke king
